<paragraph id="645D5844FFCB6802FEBDCB818E65EDAA" blockId="9.[264,813,447,473]" box="[264,813,447,473]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<typeStatus id="BB59E6E6FFCB6802FEBDCB818C0AEDAA" box="[264,322,447,473]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Type</typeStatus>
species: 
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFCB6802FE00CB818FC2EDAB" authority="Blahnik Table Of Contents, 2005" authorityName="Blahnik Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[437,650,447,472]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Alterosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bocainae" status="new species">
<emphasis id="56968456FFCB6802FE00CB818FC2EDAB" box="[437,650,447,472]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Alterosa bocainae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="4DA5392DFFCB6802FD2CCB818E61EDAA" box="[665,809,447,473]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="645D5844FFCB6802FEBDC82A8F11E8DD" blockId="9.[264,1325,532,1878]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
The single character most useful for diagnosing 
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFCB6802FC89C82A8ED6EE5E" authorityName="Blahnik Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[828,926,532,557]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Alterosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56968456FFCB6802FC89C82A8ED6EE5E" box="[828,926,532,557]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Alterosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and which may be uniquely apomorphic, is the structure of the phallobase of the male (
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FC3FC8028EBAEE25" box="[906,1010,572,598]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="15.[264,367,1579,1603]" captionTargetBox="[391,1214,447,1560]" captionTargetId="figure-132@15.[385,1224,427,1567]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 6. Alterosa bocainae, new species. Male genitalia: 6A—lateral view; 6B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 6C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 6D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046299" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046299/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Figs. 6D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FC4BC802896CEE25" box="[1022,1060,572,598]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="19.[264,368,1665,1689]" captionTargetBox="[321,1264,430,1621]" captionTargetId="figure-61@19.[305,1282,409,1638]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 8. Alterosa caparaonensis, new species. Male genitalia: 8A—lateral view; 8B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 8C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 8D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046303" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046303/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">8D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FB84C8028910EE25" box="[1073,1112,572,598]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="21.[264,367,1473,1497]" captionTargetBox="[350,1237,291,1446]" captionTargetId="figure-108@21.[335,1252,281,1449]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 9. Alterosa escova, new species. Male genitalia: 9A—lateral view; 9B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 9C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 9D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046305" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046305/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">9D</figureCitation>
), which is tubular basally and lacks the basodorsal expansion common in most philopotamids, including species in the subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFCB6802FDB5C8B28FDEEED5" authorityName="P Rambur" authorityYear="1842" box="[512,662,652,678]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chimarrinae">Chimarrinae</taxonomicName>
. Other characters of the male genitalia useful, in combination, to diagnose the genus include: intermediate appendages positioned mesally to the preanal appendages (
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FE48C8E28FC9EE85" box="[509,641,732,758]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="15.[264,367,1579,1603]" captionTargetBox="[391,1214,447,1560]" captionTargetId="figure-132@15.[385,1224,427,1567]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 6. Alterosa bocainae, new species. Male genitalia: 6A—lateral view; 6B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 6C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 6D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046299" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046299/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Figs. 6A,B</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FD38C8E28F95EE85" box="[653,733,732,758]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="22.[264,367,1796,1820]" captionTargetBox="[324,1279,540,1756]" captionTargetId="figure-93@22.[305,1282,529,1769]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 10. Alterosa falcata, new species. Male genitalia: 10A—lateral view; 10B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 10C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 10D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046307" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046307/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">10A,B</figureCitation>
), absence of ventral processes on any of the terminal segments of the male genitalia, and sternum IX with the posteroventral margin distinctly produced and widely truncate ventrally (
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FC89C9128E89EF35" box="[828,961,812,838]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="21.[264,367,1473,1497]" captionTargetBox="[350,1237,291,1446]" captionTargetId="figure-108@21.[335,1252,281,1449]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 9. Alterosa escova, new species. Male genitalia: 9A—lateral view; 9B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 9C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 9D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046305" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046305/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Figs. 9A,B</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FC7AC9128955EF35" box="[975,1053,812,838]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="22.[264,367,1796,1820]" captionTargetBox="[324,1279,540,1756]" captionTargetId="figure-93@22.[305,1282,529,1769]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 10. Alterosa falcata, new species. Male genitalia: 10A—lateral view; 10B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 10C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 10D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046307" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046307/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">10A,B</figureCitation>
) and the posterodorsal margin 
<emphasis id="56968456FFCB6802FED4C96A8CFEEF1E" box="[353,438,852,877]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">acutely</emphasis>
articulating with the tergum (
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FCA5C96A8E3FEF1D" box="[784,887,852,878]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="15.[264,367,1579,1603]" captionTargetBox="[391,1214,447,1560]" captionTargetId="figure-132@15.[385,1224,427,1567]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 6. Alterosa bocainae, new species. Male genitalia: 6A—lateral view; 6B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 6C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 6D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046299" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046299/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Figs. 6A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FC36C96A8EE3EF1D" box="[899,939,852,878]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="21.[264,367,1473,1497]" captionTargetBox="[350,1237,291,1446]" captionTargetId="figure-108@21.[335,1252,281,1449]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 9. Alterosa escova, new species. Male genitalia: 9A—lateral view; 9B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 9C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 9D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046305" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046305/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">9A</figureCitation>
). Preanal appendages arise from the base of tergum X (
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FDACC9428F31EFE5" box="[537,633,892,918]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="15.[264,367,1579,1603]" captionTargetBox="[391,1214,447,1560]" captionTargetId="figure-132@15.[385,1224,427,1567]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 6. Alterosa bocainae, new species. Male genitalia: 6A—lateral view; 6B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 6C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 6D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046299" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046299/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FD32C9428FF5EFE5" box="[647,701,892,918]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="22.[264,367,1796,1820]" captionTargetBox="[324,1279,540,1756]" captionTargetId="figure-93@22.[305,1282,529,1769]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 10. Alterosa falcata, new species. Male genitalia: 10A—lateral view; 10B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 10C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 10D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046307" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046307/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">10A</figureCitation>
), rather than the dorsal margin of sternum IX (as is typical in 
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFCB6802FE35C99A8C91EFCE" authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1918" box="[384,473,932,957]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Sortosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56968456FFCB6802FE35C99A8C91EFCE" box="[384,473,932,957]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Sortosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, see 
<bibRefCitation id="007325B5FFCB6802FDADC99A8FDEEFCD" author="Ross, H. H." box="[536,662,932,958]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" refId="ref24382" refString="Ross, H. H. (1956) Evolution and Classification of the Mountain Caddisflies. Urbana, University of Illinois Press, 213 pp." type="book" year="1956">Ross 1956</bibRefCitation>
, figs. 36A, 37A, 38A). In species in which the preanal appendages are not secondarily modified (
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FD4CC9F28E1FEF95" box="[761,855,972,998]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="21.[264,367,1473,1497]" captionTargetBox="[350,1237,291,1446]" captionTargetId="figure-108@21.[335,1252,281,1449]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 9. Alterosa escova, new species. Male genitalia: 9A—lateral view; 9B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 9C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 9D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046305" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046305/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
), they are relatively simple in structure, elongate and finger­like (
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FD98C9CA8FDEE87D" box="[557,662,1012,1038]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="15.[264,367,1579,1603]" captionTargetBox="[391,1214,447,1560]" captionTargetId="figure-132@15.[385,1224,427,1567]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 6. Alterosa bocainae, new species. Male genitalia: 6A—lateral view; 6B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 6C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 6D—phallic apparatus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046299" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046299/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Figs. 6A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FD14C9CA8F9EE87D" box="[673,726,1012,1038]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="24.[264,367,1816,1840]" captionTargetBox="[370,1232,583,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-102@24.[348,1240,578,1808]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 11. Alterosa fimbriata, new species. Male genitalia: 11A—lateral view; 11B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 11C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 11D—phallic apparatus, lateral view; 11E—dorsal view of segment VIII." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046309" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046309/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">11A</figureCitation>
). Venation (
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FCDDC9CA8EE3E87D" box="[872,939,1012,1038]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="10.[264,368,1571,1595]" captionTargetBox="[281,1312,547,1481]" captionTargetId="figure-52@10.[273,1319,509,1564]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 1. Alterosa bocainae, new species. Wings: 1A—forewing; 1B—hind wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046285" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046285/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) is primitive for 
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFCB6802FBC7C9CA8862E87D" box="[1138,1322,1012,1038]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Philopotamidae</taxonomicName>
and very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFCB6802FE4CCE228F1AE846" authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1918" box="[505,594,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Sortosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56968456FFCB6802FE4CCE228F1AE846" box="[505,594,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Sortosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFCB6802FD27CE228E71E846" authorityName="Tillyard" authorityYear="1924" box="[658,825,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Hydrobiosella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56968456FFCB6802FD27CE228E71E846" box="[658,825,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Hydrobiosella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Female genitalia (
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FB9ACE228932E845" box="[1071,1146,1052,1078]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="12.[264,368,1854,1878]" captionTargetBox="[302,1285,1489,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-372@12.[302,1285,1489,1828]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 4. Alterosa bocainae, new species. Female genitalia—lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046289" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046289/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), like those of most genera of 
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFCB6802FE0BCE7A8F31E82D" authorityName=", Ross" authorityYear="1956" box="[446,633,1092,1118]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Philopotaminae">Philopotaminae</taxonomicName>
, excluding 
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFCB6802FD4ACE7A8ED5E82E" authorityName="Ulmer" authorityYear="1909" box="[767,925,1092,1117]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Dolophilodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56968456FFCB6802FD4ACE7A8ED5E82E" box="[767,925,1092,1117]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Dolophilodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFCB6802FC1ECE7A895DE82E" authorityName="Ross" authorityYear="1956" box="[939,1045,1092,1117]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Fumonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56968456FFCB6802FC1ECE7A895DE82E" box="[939,1045,1092,1117]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fumonta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFCB6802FBE0CE7A89B0E82E" authorityName="Stephens" authorityYear="1829" box="[1109,1272,1092,1117]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Philopotamus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56968456FFCB6802FBE0CE7A89B0E82E" box="[1109,1272,1092,1117]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Philopotamus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are elongate and tapered, with very long, articulated apodemes from the anterior margin of sternum VIII and tergum IX.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="645D5844FFCB6801FE8DCE828F12ED12" blockId="9.[264,1325,532,1878]" lastBlockId="10.[264,1322,284,353]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="11" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
Adult. Color of pinned, dry specimens dark brown overall with contrasting small light brown or yellowish spots on forewings, these sometimes arranged in irregularly linear arrays near costal margins; legs, palps, and antennae usually paler in color. Three ocelli present, prominent. Eyes with short projecting setae between the ommatidia. Maxillary palps (
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FEE9CF628CE0E905" box="[348,424,1372,1398]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[264,367,1662,1686]" captionTargetBox="[290,1296,289,1643]" captionTargetId="figure-70@11.[290,1296,289,1644]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Alterosa bocainae, new species. Head and palps: 2A—lateral view; 2B—dorsal view of maxillary palp segments 1–3. FIGURE 3. Alterosa bocainae, new species. Setal warts of head and thorax—dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046287" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046287/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) 5­segmented, relatively short: 1st segment very short, usually broadly joined (often apparently fused) to 2nd segment, usually with a few setae on apicomesal margin; 2nd segment short, globose, with numerous elongate setae on apicomesal surface; 3rd segment relatively short, about 3 or 4x length of segment 2; 4th segment very short, about 2x as long as wide; 5th segment longer than segment 3, variable in length among species. Setal warts of head (Fig. 3) well developed; posterolateral warts large, typical of 
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFCB6802FEBDCC728C8CEA15" box="[264,452,1612,1638]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Philopotamidae</taxonomicName>
; posterior setal warts rounded, separated mesally; anteromesal setal wart large, subtriangular, notched mesally to accommodate anterior ocellus, laterally fused to anterior setal warts; fused anterior and anteromesal warts roughly M­shaped. Prothorax with rounded mesal setal warts, slightly separated mesally, laterally with indistinctly defined setal areas. Wing venation (
<figureCitation id="FCD944C1FFCB6802FD71CCD28E43EB75" box="[708,779,1772,1798]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="10.[264,368,1571,1595]" captionTargetBox="[281,1312,547,1481]" captionTargetId="figure-52@10.[273,1319,509,1564]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 1. Alterosa bocainae, new species. Wings: 1A—forewing; 1B—hind wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046285" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046285/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) primitive (forewing with forks 1–5 present, hind wing with fork 4 missing, anal veins of hind wing reaching wing margin); fork 1 of forewing branching just proximal to discal crossvein; 
<emphasis id="56968456FFCB6802FCCACD028EC2EB26" box="[895,906,1852,1877]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">s</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="56968456FFCB6802FC2CCD028E8BEB26" box="[921,963,1852,1877]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">r­m</emphasis>
, and m crossveins of forewing nearly linearly arranged, these plus 
<emphasis id="56968456FFC86801FD0ECB228FBDED46" box="[699,757,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">m­cu</emphasis>
, base of fork 3, and apex of Cu 
<subScript id="F8665A01FFC86801FB35CB1689C2ED4A" attach="left" box="[1152,1162,296,313]" fontSize="7" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">2</subScript>
clear, unpigmented. Spur formula 2:4:4.
</paragraph>
<caption id="309D08CCFFC86801FEBDCC1D89E2EA49" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046285" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5046285" box="[264,1194,1571,1595]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046285/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" startId="10.[264,368,1571,1595]" targetBox="[281,1312,547,1481]" targetPageId="10">
<paragraph id="645D5844FFC86801FEBDCC1D89E2EA49" blockId="10.[264,1194,1571,1595]" box="[264,1194,1571,1595]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis id="56968456FFC86801FEBDCC1D8CC2EA48" bold="true" box="[264,394,1571,1595]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="A3E223C7FFC86801FE2DCC1D8F12EA49" authority="Blahnik Table Of Contents, 2005" authorityName="Blahnik Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[408,602,1571,1594]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Alterosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bocainae" status="new species">
<emphasis id="56968456FFC86801FE2DCC1D8F12EA49" box="[408,602,1571,1594]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Alterosa bocainae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
